          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics2-276b.jpg" id="id1171425189648__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media></equation><para id="id1171417270038">The thermal stability and bond strength of the dihydrides follows the trend: </para>
    
    <equation id="eip-615"><media id="id1171418759439_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics3-ede9.jpg" id="id1171418759439__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media></equation><para id="id1171422842448">While H<sub>2</sub>Se is thermodynamically stable to 280 °C, H<sub>2</sub>Te and H<sub>2</sub>Po are thermodynamically unstable. </para>
    <para id="id1171432196285">All the dihydrides behave as weak acids in water. Thus, dissolution of H<sub>2</sub>S is water results in the formation of the conjugate bases, <link target-id="eip-734"/> and <link target-id="eip-443"/>, with dissociation constants of 10<sup>-7</sup> and 10<sup>-17</sup>, respectively. </para>
    
