<section id="id1171451896224">
      <title>Sulfanes</title>
      <para id="id1171431229464">The propensity of sulfur for catenation means that while the hydrides of oxygen are limited to water (H<sub>2</sub>O) and hydrogen peroxide (H<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>), the compounds H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>n</sub> where n = 2 - 6 may all be isolated. Higher homologs are also known, but only as mixtures. All of the sulfanes are yellow liquids whose viscosity increases with increased chain length. </para>
      <para id="id1171444955327">A mixture of lower sulfanes is prepared by the reaction of sodium sulfides (Na<sub>2</sub>Sn) with HCl, <link target-id="eip-324"/>. From this mixture the compounds H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>n</sub> where n = 2 - 5 are purified by fractional distillation. However, higher sulfanes are made by the reaction of either H<sub>2</sub>S or H<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub> with sulfur chlorides, <link target-id="eip-152"/> and <link target-id="eip-788"/>. </para>
      
